+# Module 1 ¬∑ Lesson 03 Video Script ‚Äî German Sounds for Malayalam Speakers
+
+Updated: 2026-06-02 15:20 CEST
+
+**Purpose:** Train the highest-risk beginner sounds early so learners can say greetings and first sentences confidently.
+
+**Presenter language:** Boss records explanation later in Malayalam/Manglish. This script uses English stage directions plus exact German/on-screen text.
+
+**Target length:** 45 minutes.
+
+**Learner output by end:** Shadow 10 lines using `ch`, `sch`, German `w/v`, and umlauts; recognise the dangerous differences.
+
+---
+
+## 0:00‚Äì1:00 ‚Äî Hook: accent is not the goal; being understood is
+
+**Visual:** Learner says `Ich lerne Deutsch.`; audio waveform highlights `ich` and `Deutsch`.
+
+**Presenter:**
+
+[Boss explains in Malayalam/Manglish: ‚ÄúWe are not trying to sound native today. We are preventing the few pronunciation mistakes that can block understanding.‚Äù]
+
+**On-screen:**
+
+```text
+Goal: clear A1 German.
+Not perfect accent.
+```
+
+**Practice pause:**
+
+> Say once: **Ich lerne Deutsch.**
+
+---
+
+## 1:00‚Äì6:30 ‚Äî Sound 1: soft `ch` in `ich`
+
+**Teaching point:** After front vowels like `i`, German `ch` is a soft sound. Do not turn every `ich` into `isch`.
+
+**On-screen:**
+
+```text
+ich ‚âÝ isch
+Ich lerne Deutsch.
+```
+
+**Presenter:**
+
+[Boss explains in Malayalam/Manglish: Put the tongue near the top/front of the mouth; let air pass softly. Do not make a full Malayalam/English ‚Äúsh‚Äù sound. Good enough is fine.]
+
+**Drill:**
+
+1. **ich**
+2. **Ich**
+3. **Ich lerne.**
+4. **Ich lerne Deutsch.**
+
+Pause 3 seconds after each.
+
+**Tiny discrimination check:**
+
+Presenter says two versions:
+
+- A: `ich` with soft `ch`
+- B: `isch`
+
+Learner chooses which is better for standard German.
+
+**Answer:** A.
+
+---
+
+## 6:30‚Äì12:00 ‚Äî Sound 2: `sch` is allowed, but only where written
+
+**Teaching point:** German `sch` is like ‚Äúsh‚Äù. It appears in words such as `sch√∂n`. Do not use it for every `ch`.
+
+**On-screen table:**
+
